There are two fundamentally different things happening under the "AI knowledge management" umbrella right now and most people aren't distinguishing between them.

Karpathy's [[LLM Knowledge Bases - Andrej Karpathy|LLM wiki approach]]: feed raw sources in, AI compiles a structured knowledge base. 100 articles, 400,000 words, without writing a word. The AI does the knowledge work. The human curates the inputs.

My approach: I do the thinking. The AI [[ai-as-infrastructure-for-thinking|carries the infrastructure]]. The atoms in my vault are things I actually figured out, connected, and stress-tested. The AI helped me get there faster, surfaced things I missed, challenged assumptions. But [[ai-outputs-are-inputs|its outputs were inputs to my thinking]], not the thinking itself.

Karpathy's wiki is a reference library. My vault is a thinking trail. His is more comprehensive. Mine is more defensible. I can stand behind every note because I fought with it. [[authorship-lives-in-judgement|Authorship lives in the judgement]], not the typing.

Both are valid. But they produce different things. One produces knowledge. The other produces [[positions-not-explanations|positions]]. [[the-writing-is-a-byproduct|The writing is a byproduct]] either way, but what's underneath is different.
